##############################################

DOCUMENT();

loadMacros(
  "PGstandard.pl",
  "MathObjects.pl",
  "PGML.pl",
  "contextFraction.pl",
  "parserNumberWithUnits.pl",
  "PCCmacros.pl",
  "PGcourse.pl",
);

##############################################

Context("Fraction");
$frac = Fraction(5,9);

Context("Numeric");
Context()->variables->add(F=>'Real');
Context()->flags->set(
  reduceConstants => 0,
  reduceConstantFunctions => 0,
);
$func = Formula("$frac * (F - 32)");

$num1 = non_zero_random(-3,10,1);
$plugIn = 9*$num1+32;

Context("LimitedNumeric");
$ans = $func->eval(F=>$plugIn);
$ans = $ans->reduce;
$ans = NumberWithUnits($ans,'degC');


##############################################

TEXT(beginproblem());

BEGIN_PGML

To convert a temperature measured in degrees Fahrenheit to degrees Celsius, there is a formula: [``` C=[$func] ```] where [`C`] represents the temperature in degrees Celsius and [`F`] represents the temperature in degrees Fahrenheit.

If a temperature is [`[$plugIn] {^\circ}\text{F}`], what is that temperature measured in Celsius? [@KeyboardInstructions(q!(Use [|degC|]* for [`^{\circ}\text{C}`] and [|degF|]* for [`^{\circ}\text{F}`].)!)@]**

    [_______]{$ans}

END_PGML

##############################################

BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION

We substitute [`F=[$plugIn]`] into the formula, and we have:

    [`` C=[$frac](F-32)``]

    [`` C=[$frac]([$plugIn]-32) ``]

    [`` C=[$frac] \cdot [$plugIn-32] ``]

    [`` C=[$ans]. ``]

So the temperature is [`[$ans]`].

END_PGML_SOLUTION

ENDDOCUMENT();


